    "jays": {
      "full_name": "Toronto Blue Jays",
      "league": "MLB",
      "record": "13-16",
      "detail": "4th in AL East",
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Jays",
        "body": "The Blue Jays are clawing back - barely. After a humbling shutout loss to Boston yesterday, Toronto answered with <strong>a 3-0 shutout victory behind Trey Yesavage's dominant return</strong>, the young right-hander throwing 5.1 scoreless innings in his first appearance since the 2025 World Series. It's the kind of statement performance this team desperately needs. At 13-16, sitting fourth in the AL East and 6.5 games back, the Jays are already in the hunt-or-go-home portion of April - a position no contender wants to occupy before May. Vladimir Guerrero Jr. continues to deliver in the clutch, recording a two-out single that broke the seal on the scoring. The bullpen held firm. But one win doesn't reverse the trajectory; this team has been inconsistent at best, oscillating between competence and collapse. <strong>Tonight's series finale against the Red Sox at 2:07 PM ET, with Eric Lauer on the mound, offers a chance to build momentum and steal a series from a division rival</strong>. Two wins in three games beats the alternative. But the calendar is unforgiving.",
        "updated": "Updated April 29, 2026"
      },
